# Project context

This is a data analyst portfolio project: a small pipeline that pulls
Florida crash data from the FDOT / Signal Four Analytics public API,
cleans it in pandas, aggregates it in DuckDB, and exports CSVs for a
Tableau Public dashboard.

The audience is a hiring manager reviewing the GitHub repo and a
LinkedIn writeup, and the author defending the work in an interview.

# How to help

- Prefer pandas and DuckDB. Don't reach for Spark, Airflow, dbt, or any
  heavier orchestrator — the whole project should run on a laptop.
- Keep code well-commented for interview defense: every non-trivial step
  should be readable to someone seeing it for the first time, with a
  short comment explaining *why* (not just what).
- Don't over-engineer. No premature abstraction, no config systems, no
  retry/backoff frameworks unless something concrete requires it. A
  straight-line script is the right shape here.
- Keep the pipeline reproducible: raw pulls land in data/raw/ and are
  never mutated; clean.py reads from there and writes to data/processed/.
- SQL aggregations live in sql/ as plain .sql files invoked from
  clean.py so they're easy to review on their own.
- Tableau Public can only read CSVs from disk, so processed/ outputs
  should be flat CSVs, one per dashboard view.
